The Economics of Violence
COPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine and elsewhere are constantly in the news and therefore many would probably say war.
But this turns out to be a big mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-effective solutions to this and other global problems.
It is obvious that everyone would like to end every war and violence, just as we would like to end poverty, hunger, and global warming and provide all people with access to education.
However, given limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We must set priorities, and for this an economic cost-benefit analysis can be used.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to assess which goals, in their view, would be the smartest.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the use of resources that could otherwise, for example, be used to combat hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at Oxford University, violence within society – murders and especially violence against women and children – is a much greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die from interpersonal violence, and for every two fighters who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and far too many countries record murder rates of over 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization refers to as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs one person's life and society 9.1 million US dollars.
Measured by global national income, this form of violent crime alone costs 1.7% of the global gross social product (GDP).
Of course, this is not a direct financial loss for the world economy, but rather a way of expressing the consequences.
If murders could be abolished, societies around the world would be better off in a way that can be measured in 1.7% of GDP.
Compare this with the much lower costs of civil wars, which amount to about 0.2% of global GDP.
However, this is still much less than the greatest source of violence altogether: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence from their life partners or family members last year.
This includes women who were beaten, forced to marry at a young age, exposed to sexual violence, and became victims of crimes committed in the name of "honor" and female genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the societal costs alone from violence by intimate partners amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars or 5.2% of global GDP.
The second largest source of violence is the abuse of children, which is committed by parents in 80% of cases.
The definition of what constitutes child abuse varies from culture to culture, but about 15% of children experience what the UN refers to as severe physical punishment every month.
These include slaps to the face, head, or ears, and a quarter of these children are beaten repeatedly and as hard as possible with an object.
This suffering affects about 290 million children every month.
The social costs amount to 3.6 trillion US dollars or 4.2% of global GDP.
Only a tiny fraction of international aid funds is currently flowing into reducing violence in society and improving criminal justice systems.
The enormous costs borne by society and individuals scream out for action to be taken.
Unfortunately, there is still little solid knowledge about where the limited resources should be best used.
All that can be said is that the money spent on reducing violence could be used more targetedly.
Large sums of aid are allocated to "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the component "crime prevention".
Other programs can contribute indirectly, yet obviously much could be improved.
Some solutions, as is clear, work very well.
More capable social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the U.S. state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve children's quality of life and their physical and mental health, and lower the costs of care and legal proceedings.
One dollar spent on this program produces a benefit worth 14 U.S. dollars: it is thus an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program in Uganda called SASA! is working on this.
(Swahili for "Now!") to spread the message that violence in relationships is unacceptable and has contributed to halving the number of cases.
This is a fantastic result, even though there is no analysis of cost-effectiveness available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures have been taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach – a time limit for alcohol sales, reclaiming public space, and improvements in the police and justice system – the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants by 2004.
This is still a high number, but far below the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many violent attacks, and the insights from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of significant importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on better enforcement of existing regulations showed that violent attacks could be reduced in a very cost-effective manner, with the benefits outweighing the costs by a ratio of 17 to 1.
We still do not know enough, but two points are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children imposes societal costs of 8 trillion US dollars per year, making it a huge – and far too overlooked – global problem.
Second, there are solutions that can help address some of these problems in a very cost-effective way.
For this reason, the reduction of domestic violence belongs to the shortlist for the next global development goals.
